 1334: /**
 1335:  * Package os provides a platform-independent interface to operating system
 1336:  * functionality. The design is Unix-like, although the error handling is
 1337:  * Go-like; failing calls return values of type error rather than error numbers.
 1338:  * Often, more information is available within the error. For example,
 1339:  * if a call that takes a file name fails, such as [Open] or [Stat], the error
 1340:  * will include the failing file name when printed and will be of type
 1341:  * [*PathError], which may be unpacked for more information.
 1342:  * 
 1343:  * The os interface is intended to be uniform across all operating systems.
 1344:  * Features not generally available appear in the system-specific package syscall.
 1345:  * 
 1346:  * Here is a simple example, opening a file and reading some of it.
 1347:  * 
 1348:  * ```
 1349:  * 	file, err := os.Open("file.go") // For read access.
 1350:  * 	if err != nil {
 1351:  * 		log.Fatal(err)
 1352:  * 	}
 1353:  * ```
 1354:  * 
 1355:  * If the open fails, the error string will be self-explanatory, like
 1356:  * 
