 5800: /**
 5801:  * Package exec runs external commands. It wraps os.StartProcess to make it
 5802:  * easier to remap stdin and stdout, connect I/O with pipes, and do other
 5803:  * adjustments.
 5804:  * 
 5805:  * Unlike the "system" library call from C and other languages, the
 5806:  * os/exec package intentionally does not invoke the system shell and
 5807:  * does not expand any glob patterns or handle other expansions,
 5808:  * pipelines, or redirections typically done by shells. The package
 5809:  * behaves more like C's "exec" family of functions. To expand glob
 5810:  * patterns, either call the shell directly, taking care to escape any
 5811:  * dangerous input, or use the [path/filepath] package's Glob function.
 5812:  * To expand environment variables, use package os's ExpandEnv.
 5813:  * 
 5814:  * Note that the examples in this package assume a Unix system.
 5815:  * They may not run on Windows, and they do not run in the Go Playground
 5816:  * used by golang.org and godoc.org.
 5817:  * 
 5818:  * # Executables in the current directory
 5819:  * 
 5820:  * The functions [Command] and [LookPath] look for a program
 5821:  * in the directories listed in the current path, following the
 5822:  * conventions of the host operating system.
 5823:  * Operating systems have for decades included the current
 5824:  * directory in this search, sometimes implicitly and sometimes
 5825:  * configured explicitly that way by default.
 5826:  * Modern practice is that including the current directory
 5827:  * is usually unexpected and often leads to security problems.
 5828:  * 
 5829:  * To avoid those security problems, as of Go 1.19, this package will not resolve a program
 5830:  * using an implicit or explicit path entry relative to the current directory.
 5831:  * That is, if you run [LookPath]("go"), it will not successfully return
 5832:  * ./go on Unix nor .\go.exe on Windows, no matter how the path is configured.
 5833:  * Instead, if the usual path algorithms would result in that answer,
 5834:  * these functions return an error err satisfying [errors.Is](err, [ErrDot]).
 5835:  * 
 5836:  * For example, consider these two program snippets:
 5837:  * 
 5838:  * ```
 5839:  * 	path, err := exec.LookPath("prog")
 5840:  * 	if err != nil {
 5841:  * 		log.Fatal(err)
 5842:  * 	}
 5843:  * 	use(path)
 5844:  * ```
 5845:  * 
 5846:  * and
 5847:  * 
 5848:  * ```
 5849:  * 	cmd := exec.Command("prog")
 5850:  * 	if err := cmd.Run(); err != nil {
 5851:  * 		log.Fatal(err)
 5852:  * 	}
 5853:  * ```
 5854:  * 
 5855:  * These will not find and run ./prog or .\prog.exe,
 5856:  * no matter how the current path is configured.
 5857:  * 
 5858:  * Code that always wants to run a program from the current directory
 5859:  * can be rewritten to say "./prog" instead of "prog".
 5860:  * 
 5861:  * Code that insists on including results from relative path entries
 5862:  * can instead override the error using an errors.Is check:
 5863:  * 
 5864:  * ```
 5865:  * 	path, err := exec.LookPath("prog")
 5866:  * 	if errors.Is(err, exec.ErrDot) {
 5867:  * 		err = nil
 5868:  * 	}
 5869:  * 	if err != nil {
 5870:  * 		log.Fatal(err)
 5871:  * 	}
 5872:  * 	use(path)
 5873:  * ```
 5874:  * 
 5875:  * and
 5876:  * 
 5877:  * ```
 5878:  * 	cmd := exec.Command("prog")
 5879:  * 	if errors.Is(cmd.Err, exec.ErrDot) {
 5880:  * 		cmd.Err = nil
 5881:  * 	}
 5882:  * 	if err := cmd.Run(); err != nil {
 5883:  * 		log.Fatal(err)
 5884:  * 	}
 5885:  * ```
 5886:  * 
 5887:  * Setting the environment variable GODEBUG=execerrdot=0
 5888:  * disables generation of ErrDot entirely, temporarily restoring the pre-Go 1.19
 5889:  * behavior for programs that are unable to apply more targeted fixes.
 5890:  * A future version of Go may remove support for this variable.
 5891:  * 
 5892:  * Before adding such overrides, make sure you understand the
 5893:  * security implications of doing so.
 5894:  * See https://go.dev/blog/path-security for more information.
 5895:  */
 5896: namespace exec {
 5897:  interface command {
 5898:   /**
 5899:    * Command returns the [Cmd] struct to execute the named program with
 5900:    * the given arguments.
 5901:    * 
 5902:    * It sets only the Path and Args in the returned structure.
 5903:    * 
 5904:    * If name contains no path separators, Command uses [LookPath] to
 5905:    * resolve name to a complete path if possible. Otherwise it uses name
 5906:    * directly as Path.
 5907:    * 
 5908:    * The returned Cmd's Args field is constructed from the command name
 5909:    * followed by the elements of arg, so arg should not include the
 5910:    * command name itself. For example, Command("echo", "hello").
 5911:    * Args[0] is always name, not the possibly resolved Path.
 5912:    * 
 5913:    * On Windows, processes receive the whole command line as a single string
 5914:    * and do their own parsing. Command combines and quotes Args into a command
 5915:    * line string with an algorithm compatible with applications using
 5916:    * CommandLineToArgvW (which is the most common way). Notable exceptions are
 5917:    * msiexec.exe and cmd.exe (and thus, all batch files), which have a different
 5918:    * unquoting algorithm. In these or other similar cases, you can do the
 5919:    * quoting yourself and provide the full command line in SysProcAttr.CmdLine,
 5920:    * leaving Args empty.
 5921:    */
 5922:   (name: string, ...arg: string[]): (Cmd)
 5923:  }
 5924: }
